title: TheThreeWorldsTheory
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

Popper proposes that reality consists of three interacting worlds:

|! World |! Description |! Examples |
| World 1 | The physical world | Stones, atoms, the brain, sunlight. |
| World 2 | The psychological world | Feelings, thoughts, dreams, subjective perceptions. |
| World 3 | The world of objective knowledge | Scientific theories, math, books, music, cultural heritage. |

!! Interaction

''W2 acts as a bridge: World 3 (theories) cannot influence World 1 (physical objects) directly. A human mind (W2) must grasp the theory (W3) to build a machine (W1).''

@@Autonomy of W3: Once a theory is written down, it exists independently of its creator and can have unintended consequences.@@